body:
@Johny-Kandhari All I can say is that this is the first time problem has been reported so it probably has to be quite unusual use case or setup.

One guess I do have from stack trace: if application or framework in use specifies custom deserializers, one of them may not be properly propagating calls to `resolve()` method, which could perhaps lead to some state being left incomplete. This would happen when for example custom deserializer was wrapping standard one, created via `BeanDeserializerModifier`: both `resolve()` (via `ResolvableDeserializer`) and `createContextual` (via `ContextualDeserializer`) should be propagated as they are the mechanism to resolve cyclic type dependencies (resolve) and access to contextual information (annotations).

Another possibility wrt custom deserializers could be if `BeanDeserializer` was sub-classes: while this is not encouraged (sub-classing here is fragile, but can not be prevented) it is sometimes done as work-around.
